  <purpose>&lt;p&gt;
    The use-case model is useful when considered together with its related work products: &lt;u&gt;Use Cases&lt;/u&gt; and
    &lt;u&gt;Actors&lt;/u&gt;.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
    In general,&amp;nbsp;a use-case model&amp;nbsp;presents an overview of the system, serving as basis for an agreement between
    customers and project team of the intended functionality for the system. It also helps to drive the various tasks in
    the software development lifecycle. Refer to &lt;u&gt;Work Product: Use Cases&lt;/u&gt; for additional information.
&lt;/p&gt;</purpose>
  <representationOptions>&lt;p&gt;

    Tailor to support project needs.&amp;nbsp;Projects may not to include the use-case model as one of the work

    products being created.&amp;nbsp;Identifying actors and use cases, then describing the use-cases scenarios

    are&amp;nbsp;recommended tasks though.&amp;nbsp;

&lt;/p&gt;

